post_text:
Dear 7th Grade Students and Families,
Although we will begin the school year in a virtual environment, we are still very excited to welcome our new students and families to the Lakeland High School community. This week, we will be sharing our Virtual 7th Grade Orientation to student emails and also to the Official Lakeland School District Facebook Page. Folders will also be mailed, which will include important information such as student schedules, Live session times, Student Handbook changes, and a map of the High School building.
We look forward to seeing all of our new faces and wish everyone an awesome 2020-2021 school year! For further information, please contact the High School Office at 570-254-9485, extension 2000.
Thank you,
Mrs. Bullick and Mr. Rosenkrans

Fully Virtual Instruction will begin on Monday, August 31st. If you are in need of a district chromebook, we will be distributing at the Lakeland High School on the following days:
11th and 12th Grade- Tuesday, August 11th from 1-3PM
9th and 10th Grade- Wednesday, August 12th from 4-6PM
7th and 8th Grade- Thursday, August 13th from 4-6PM

Please use the entrance by Scott Elementary off Route 247. Pickup will be at the Main Entrance of the High School.

Senior Families,

We will be handing out stoles and pins tomorrow afternoon from 1-3PM in front of the High School. Thank you and have a wonderful day!

NOTICE OF MEETINGS FORMAT CHANGE

The regular monthly business meeting of the Lakeland Board of Education will be conducted at 7:00 p.m. on Wednesday, May 20, 2020. All meetings will be held virtually on Zoom for the Board & Administration participants only and will be live streamed for the public to view at Facebook.com/lakelandchiefs. Meeting agendas will be posted on the District website at www.lakelandsd.org.

Public comment on agenda items only for the Wednesday, May 20th Board Meeting can be made by clicking on the link on the Lakeland School District website or Facebook page utilizing the Google form for public comment and will be received up to 6:00 p.m. on Wednesday, May 20, 2020. Anyone requiring reasonable accommodation to access the meeting due to a disability should email the School District or contact the District office at 570-254-9485.

Thomas Walsh, Board Secretary

http://www.lakelandsd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=434125&type=d&pREC_ID=943395

We know the coronavirus has created challenges for AP students and teachers. Here‚Äôs how the College Board will support you during this time:

1Ô∏è‚É£ We‚Äôre providing free, live and on-demand AP courses

To support AP students affected by school closures due to COVID-19, students and schools will have access to live AP review lessons, delivered by AP teachers from across the country. Lessons will begin March 25.

2Ô∏è‚É£ We‚Äôre developing a new at-home testing option

Because of the challenges created by COVID-19, we‚Äôre developing a new at-home AP Exam option. Students will be able to test on a computer, tablet, or smartphone.

We will invest so that every AP student impacted by COVID-19 has the tools and connectivity they need to review AP content online and take the exam from home.

During this challenging time, we will work to give every AP student the opportunity to earn the college credit and placement they‚Äôve been working toward all year while maintaining a focus on the health and safety of our AP community.

More details here: http://spr.ly/61851tbn3.

Lakeland High School is now a Wishpartner with Make a Wish! Our "Believe" letter campaign organized by Evan Magnotta collected 1463 letters that will grant wishes of children with critical illnesses.
Our very own, Gia Grier, could not think of anything more magical than meeting her favorite Disney characters and spending a week with her family visiting the Castle of Miracles, an Ice Cream Palace (with all the ice-cream she could eat), and the gingerbread house restaurant.
Pictured below is Gia with some of her biggest fans, members of the Boys Varsity Basketball Team, who presented Gia with her very own uniform and signed basketball. Gia is our warrior!!

post_text:
Evan Magnotta chose to participate in his first Kids For Wish Kids this year by raising money to help fund local wishes for children with life threatening illnesses. In early November "wish boxes" were placed at Lakeland High School, Scott Elementary and the Mayfield Campus. Requests were sent out asking for holiday letters, holiday drawings, and cards to be deposited into the boxes. For every submission, the Macys department store would donate $1.00 to Make A Wish. The average cost for one wish is $4,400.

On December 20, 2019, Evan collected, counted, and deposited 1,463 submissions. All submissions were delivered to MACYS red mailbox. Evan had hoped for a minimum of 300 submissions and was ecstatic he surpassed it by more than 1000.

Next year, Evan is trying for even more!
